              "mainEntity": [
                {
                  "@type": "Question",
                  "name": "Why is Inconel 718 so commonly used?",
                  "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "Because Inconel 718 boasts superior overall performance. Firstly, its chromium and molybdenum content ensures excellent corrosion resistance. Nickel allows Inconel 718 to operate at high temperatures. Simultaneously, precipitation strengthening gives the alloy very high strength. Therefore, Inconel 718 is ideal for use in extreme environments."
                  }
                },
                {
                  "@type": "Question",
                  "name": "I'd like to know how to purchase your products?",
                  "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "You can tell us your needs via email at sales@aeether.com, or submit the form below the page. Our sales team will send you a detailed quotation. If you are satisfied with our quotation, please send us your PO file. We will provide you with a PI for payment arrangements. We will begin production after receiving the prepayment. We will notify you as soon as the materials are completed."
                  }
                },
                {
                  "@type": "Question",
                  "name": "Why do different products have different mechanical properties?",
                  "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "Differences in mechanical properties may be influenced by several factors: 1) Different manufacturing processes for various products; 2) Differences in cold working and heat treatment methods; 3) Differences in product dimensions and specifications."
                  }
                },
                {
                  "@type": "Question",
                  "name": "What is precipitation strengthening?",
                  "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "Precipitation strengthening is a unique strengthening mechanism found in certain alloys, and not all alloys possess this characteristic. These alloys can undergo aging treatment, a heat treatment process that induces the precipitation of fine strengthening phases, significantly improving their strength. Key elements determining whether an alloy exhibits precipitation strengthening properties include aluminum, titanium, niobium, and tantalum."
                  }
                },
                {
                  "@type": "Question",
                  "name": "What do the UNS and W.Nr. designations mean?",
                  "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "They are both numbering systems established to standardize material designation. The purpose of these systems is to ensure that each grade corresponds to a unique designation, thus eliminating ambiguity in terminology. In practical applications, the US standard system tends to use UNS designations, while the European standard system more often uses W.Nr. designations."
                  }
                },
                {
                  "@type": "Question",
                  "name": "Is shipping handled by you or do we arrange it ourselves?",
                  "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "According to the default trade terms, we use FOB delivery. This means you can freely choose your freight forwarder to arrange transportation, and we will cooperate with your freight forwarder to complete all local export formalities. Of course, if you prefer us to handle the transportation, we can also arrange it for you and provide a corresponding shipping quote."
                  }
                },
                {
                  "@type": "Question",
                  "name": "How do I understand the concept of tensile strength?",
                  "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "Tensile strength is a core indicator in the material strength evaluation system. It characterizes the ultimate stress a material can withstand from elastic deformation to final fracture under tension. If your application requires the material to be as resistant to breakage as possible, then tensile strength is a priority indicator when selecting materials. Furthermore, tensile strength can also indirectly reflect the overall strength characteristics of a material."
                  }
                }
